The paper focuses on the analysis and testing of non-functional requirements in software engineering, which falls under the scope of cs.SE (Software Engineering). The paper also discusses the classification and documentation of requirements, which is related to cs.PL (Programming Languages). The empirical investigation of requirements specifications suggests that many non-functional requirements describe system behavior, which is relevant to cs.SD (Software Development) and cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction). Finally, the paper addresses the practical implications of handling non-functional requirements, which could be relevant to cs.CY (Computers and Society).
